Re layout: it really doesn&#39;t matter; you do you. Consistency in the project and/or team would be nice, but **the compiler doesn&#39;t care**. Personally, I&#39;d say the layout might depend on the length of the individual arguments, and whether any of them are associated with their neighbors, or form logical groups.

Re the actual *practice* of having many arguments; *consider* using a type to represent them all instead; methods with lots of arguments tend to gradually grow *even more* over time, making it necessary to break the signature. A single state parameter avoids that:

``` c#
public void Method(Foo foo)
{
}
```

The `Foo` here could be a `class`, or perhaps a `readonly struct`

